body: @wejoncy Cheng,  thanks for checkin the XNNPACK basic QDQ operator support, could u please help to check this issue?

How was the model created? It has an explicit import for an internal domain with an incorrect opset version. The value of com.ms.internal.nhwc should match the ai.onnx version. It's somewhat unexpected that the model would have that as an import as that domain is intended for runtime-only internal usage by ORT.

This will fix that issue, but the original model is strangely using a very old ONNX format (IR version 3 which is many years old) and fails the onnx checker. 

```python
import onnx

model_filename = 'resnet50-v1-7_quant_QDQ.onnx'
m = onnx.load(model_filename)

# original model fails this check if uncommented due to ONNX IR version 3 requiring all initializers to be inputs
# onnx.checker.check_model(m)

onnx_opset = -1
for entry in m.opset_import:
    if entry.domain == 'ai.onnx' or entry.domain == '':  # empty string == onnx domain
        onnx_opset = entry. version

for entry in m.opset_import:
    if entry.domain == 'com.ms.internal.nhwc':
        entry.version = onnx_opset

onnx.save(m, model_filename.replace('.onnx', '.updated.onnx'))
```

The fixed model will fail with this error, so that's multiple things about the model which are unexpected/incorrect.

    [ONNXRuntimeError] : 2 : INVALID_ARGUMENT : Invalid model. Node input 'resnetv17_stage1_activation0_DequantizeLinear_token_238' is not a graph input, initializer, or output of a previous node.

I think that is due to how pytorch exports a QDQ format model (multiple consumers of a single DQ node) and would normally be fixed by running `python -m onnxruntime.tools.qdq_helpers.optimize_qdq_model <model.onnx> <fixed_model.onnx>` but due to the onnx checker failing, which is run as part of that script, it's unable to update the model.

@skottmckay   thanks for your quick reply,   here is the step of how I got this model,  
1,  download the float model from https://github.com/onnx/models/blob/main/vision/classification/resnet/model/resnet50-v1-7.onnx

2,  quantize this float model with script/example of onnxruntime quantization script at: 
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/main/quantization/image_classification/cpu/run.py

3, got the quantized model and run with the onnxruntime inference engine with XNNPACK.  

could u please take a look and see if something wrong?

thanks

@JasonMaojinsong  I think `python -m onnxruntime.tools.qdq_helpers.optimize_qdq_model <model.onnx> <fixed_model.onnx>` would be still required for this model. Then you will see each `conv/add` have its own DQ/Q nodes.

Add this after onnx.load to update the IR to v4 (which doesn't require initializers to be inputs) and to validate.

```python
m = onnx.load(model_filename)
m.ir_version = 4
onnx.checker.check_model(m)
```

After that the QDQ optimizer script should work with the updated model.

I would guess the quantization script assumes the model uses IR v4 or later, so when it adds new initializers it does not add a matching graph input. IR v3 is very old, so that's not overly surprising.

@skottmckay @wejoncy many thanks, it's working now, 
1,  it make sense that the initalizer should not put in graph input, so the quantization script should update ir_version before saving the output model. 
2,  the version to domain "com.ms.internal.nhwc" has been update to 17 on the latest onnxruntime quantization package. 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/95834241/188575106-70491b36-2d2d-453d-9ef5-211e7c626c55.png)

3,  I still don't understand why onnxruntime.tools.qdq_helpers.optimize_qdq_model can fix the issue:
[ONNXRuntimeError] : 2 : INVALID_ARGUMENT : Invalid model. Node input 'resnetv17_stage1_activation0_DequantizeLinear_token_238' is not a graph input, initializer, or output of a previous node.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/95834241/188575975-706019d7-1f0f-432b-a38b-fcc6d4a778b3.png)
looks this node has two consumer edges.

> 2, the version to domain "com.ms.internal.nhwc" has been update to 17 on the latest onnxruntime quantization package.

That just means ORT is aware of ONNX opset 17 as the internal domain is 1:1 with the ONNX op schemas with the only difference being they use NHWC layout instead of NCHW. The opset import for the internal domain should not need to be manually set in the onnx model. It MUST match the imported ONNX opset as we convert an ONNX operator to the internal domain with the assumption there are no opset differences to handle.

The QDQ handling in ORT assumes a DQ node will not have 2 output edges as it makes the processing a lot more complicated. The script will duplicate the DQ node so this doesn't happen. There's no strict definition of what a QDQ format model should conform to, so things like this can occur. We can look at moving the logic in the script into an optimizer that runs as part of ORT so the extra step isn't required.
many thanks,  it's clear to me now.   :)
